The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | 100 killed in rain rage
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     100 killed in rain rage
          OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT                              
	Hyderabad, Aug. 10: Computers, furniture and television sets from flooded homes floated down Hyderabads drains and canals as 30 hours of non-stop rain killed up to 100 people in Andhra Pradesh since yesterday.        
	Authorities plied boats on the streets to evacuate slum dwellers in the state capital, where 14 people died and swirling waters paralysed life, even submerging the IT corridor at Hitec City and Madhapur.        
	Harried police and civic authorities implored people to stay indoors and schools and colleges announced holidays yesterday. Government offices and banks were shut anyway because it was the second Saturday of the month.        
	As house collapses, drowning and electrocutions took their toll, electricity was cut off to the low-lying areas around Husseinsagar lake.        
	The largest single casualty list came from Guntur, where a truck carrying over 50 people was washed away by the surging Maddur Vagu stream this morning. Ten swam to safety and seven bodies were found, the police said, adding that the remaining 30-odd were feared dead.        
	The rain had begun on Friday night and stopped only this morning, leaving a trail of devastation in 10 districts, the worst hit being West Godavari, Hyderabad, Krishna and Khammam. Krishna recorded 200mm of rainfall and Hyderabad 180mm.        
	Hyderabad was converted into a giant lake dotted with specks  the roofs of stranded vehicles. The citys list of dead included two children and a pregnant woman, buried under the rubble of their home.        
	Irrigation tanks burst their banks and flooded villages and towns, driving residents to higher areas and relief camps. The relief commissioner in charge of disaster management at the state secretariat, K. Ratnaprabha, said nearly 10,000 displaced people had taken shelter in 100 relief camps since yesterday morning.        
	Standing crops have been damaged in over 1.6 lakh hectares, 300 irrigation tanks have been breached and over 140 villages flooded in Krishna, Khammam, Guntur and Srikakulam, she said.        
	 Boats rowed slum dwellers to safety in Hyderabads Arundhatinagar and helicopters joined rescue efforts in the districts.                                                                                                                                                                          
